{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17523212","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17523212"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:54:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:54:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13885"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13885","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13885"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.64,0.03,0.05,0.18]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6502"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109973"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6502","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6502"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13885"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92332"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1336"},{"type":"tags","id":"2192"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12922"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31327"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37211"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109973","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109973"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the General Practitioner with a dog bite to her right hand that occurred two hours ago. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a 2 cm laceration over the dorsum of her right hand with surrounding erythema. There is no evidence of tendon or nerve injury, and capillary refill is normal. The wound has been thoroughly cleaned and debrided.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate antibiotic management for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral ciprofloxacin","Oral amoxicillin/clavulanic acid","Intravenous ceftriaxone","Oral doxycycline","No antibiotics required"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate antibiotic management for this patient is \u003Cstrong\u003Eoral amoxicillin/clavulanic acid\u003C/strong\u003E. Dog bites to the hand carry a high risk of infection due to the complex anatomy and potential for deep inoculation of bacteria. Amoxicillin/clavulanic acid is the first-line antibiotic for dog bite prophylaxis because it provides coverage against the common oral flora found in dog bites, including Pasteurella species, streptococci, staphylococci, and anaerobes. Rabies is not found in dogs in Australia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral ciprofloxacin\u003C/strong\u003E does not provide adequate coverage against anaerobes and some gram-positive organisms commonly found in dog bites. It is not a first-line choice for this indication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous ceftriaxone\u003C/strong\u003E would be overly broad and unnecessary for an uncomplicated dog bite in an otherwise healthy patient. Oral antibiotics are generally sufficient for outpatient management of dog bites.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral doxycycline\u003C/strong\u003E can be considered as an alternative in patients with penicillin allergy, but it is not the first-line choice due to incomplete coverage of some potential pathogens.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile proper wound care is crucial, the option of \u003Cstrong\u003Eno antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate in this case. Given the location of the bite on the hand and the high risk of infection, antibiotic prophylaxis is recommended. The decision to prescribe antibiotics for animal bites depends on various factors, including the location of the bite, depth of the wound, time since injury, and the patient\u0027s immune status.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Amoxicillin/clavulanic acid is the first-line antibiotic for dog bite prophylaxis due to its coverage of common oral flora.","Dog bites to the hand carry a high risk of infection and often require antibiotic prophylaxis.","Wound care, including thorough cleaning and debridement, is essential in managing animal bites."],"references":["Presutti RJ. Prevention and treatment of dog bites. American Family Physician [Internet]. 2001 Apr 15 [cited 2024 Jul 26];63(8):1567\u201372. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/11327433/","Savu AN, Schoenbrunner AR, Politi R, Janis JE. Practical Review of the Management of Animal Bites. Plast Reconstr Surg Glob Open. 2021 Sep 9;9(9):e3778. doi: 10.1097/GOX.0000000000003778. PMID: 34522565; PMCID: PMC8432645. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8432645/","Morgan M, Palmer J. Dog bites. BMJ. 2007 Feb 24;334(7590):413-7. doi: 10.1136/bmj.39105.659919.BE. PMID: 17322257; PMCID: PMC1804160. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC1804160/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92332"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13885"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92332","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92332"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-27T19:04:30+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-27T19:04:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6502"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109973"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"s